This is a great breakfast cake. I found this recipe while browsing for something tasty to use some Rome apples in. It sounded simple, but I was wondering what the timing would turn out like since everyone seemed to have issue with that. I was out of O.J. so used milk instead as one reviewer said they did and I didn't have a springform so used a 9x13. I got a little concerned when 1/2 the batter only barely covered the bottom of the pan. I was surprised at all the apples I had (used 3 big Romes and 2 smaller), but just placed them all alongside eachother anyway, sometimes snapping the pieces in 1/2 to fill small voids. After dusting with the cin-sugar, I seriously started to think I was going to have a problem when the second half of the batter didn't even cover some places. But the rest of the apples got stacked in, and dusted with the cin-sugar and the whole experiment was popped into a 350 oven. 1/2 hour later I could smell it, and was surprised to see it doming! No wonder everyone's smaller pans overflowed - this is the expanding cake for certain! I'd set the timer for 80 min as the recipe suggested even though everyone else said longer, but was thinking it smelled to strongly to not be near ready at 40 min. I cooked for 65 just to be sure, but given the pan I used - it was slightly overcooked. The sides were darker, but the top looked good. I really wouldn't go over 60 min if I used the same pan again(or even a tube/bundt pan). Maybe because of overflow problems, 2 pans would be good if using a 9". Other than using milk (and I'd try apple juice next time if out of O.J.) there were no changes to the rest of the ingredient list. It was simple, and good the next morning warmed with coffee.

Rating: 2
Here is how to make this recipe delicious: 1) Use the best tasting eating apples such as Honey-crisp, Gala, Braeburn, Granny etc. Do not use a bland, mushy apple like Rome, Red Delicious or Mackintosh etc. 2) Add extra flavor wherever you can! Mix the apples with cinnamon, nutmeg and cloves, maybe even a little grand marinier 3) Add the same spices to the dry mix. To the wet ingredients I added some orange extract, but you could add lemon extract too. 4) Use a bundt or tube pan. I got good results with a tube pan lined with parchment paper. I sprayed the pan with PAM and added flour for good measure. 5. Add some nuts to the topping for crunch (optional). Finally, add as many apples as you want to add! The pan will seem full of apples, but it's ok because they shrink down after cooking. Don't worry about the design; the batter will expand around the apples and it doesn't matter much. The most important thing is adding flavor before baking the cake. With these additions the cake is lovely and very appropriate for any Jewish holiday except for passover!

